{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488471"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:43:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:43:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"453"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/453"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.16,0.06,0.7,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"453"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116314"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/453"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"453"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98310"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"6429"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1931"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2020"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10726"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29612"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49923"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116314"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of right-sided abdominal pain radiating to the groin. She is currently 20 weeks pregnant. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 124/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft but tender in the right flank. Urine dipstick shows microscopic haematuria.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT kidneys, ureter and bladder","Low dose CT kidneys, ureter and bladder","MRI abdomen","Ultrasound kidneys, ureter and bladder","Plain abdominal radiograph"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of renal colic (unilateral flank pain radiating to the groin with microscopic haematuria). The key consideration in this case is that the patient is pregnant, which influences the choice of imaging modality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound kidneys, ureter and bladder\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line investigation for suspected renal calculi in pregnant patients. It avoids radiation exposure to the fetus, has good sensitivity for detecting hydronephrosis (which occurs secondary to obstruction from a stone), and can identify larger stones (\u003E5 mm). While ultrasound has lower sensitivity for detecting small stones compared to CT, it is the safest initial approach in pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT kidneys, ureter and bladder\u003C/strong\u003E (CT KUB) is the gold standard for investigation of renal colic in non-pregnant patients. It has excellent sensitivity and specificity for detecting stones and can identify alternative diagnoses. However, it involves significant radiation exposure, making it contraindicated as a first-line investigation during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow dose CT kidneys, ureter and bladder\u003C/strong\u003E uses reduced radiation protocols but still involves ionizing radiation. While the radiation dose is less than 50 mGy (considered relatively safe during pregnancy), it should only be considered if ultrasound and MRI are inconclusive and a diagnosis is essential for management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E does not use ionizing radiation and is considered safe during pregnancy. It can be used as a second-line test when ultrasound fails to establish a diagnosis. However, it is less readily available, more expensive, and not as sensitive as CT for detecting small stones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain abdominal radiograph\u003C/strong\u003E (KUB X-ray) has limited sensitivity for detecting renal stones, as only radio-opaque stones (approximately 80% of stones) are visible. It also involves radiation exposure, albeit less than CT. Given its poor sensitivity and the availability of safer alternatives, it is not appropriate as the first-line investigation in pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ultrasonography is the first-line investigation for suspected renal calculi in pregnant patients.","CT KUB is the gold standard for diagnosing renal calculi but is contraindicated in pregnancy.","Clinical presentation of renal colic includes flank pain radiating to the groin and microscopic haematuria."],"references":["Sewell, J., Katz, D., Shoshany, O. and Love, C., 2017. Urolithiasis \u2013 Ten things every general practitioner should know. Australian Family Physician, 47(9), pp.648-652.","Masselli, G., Weston, M., and Spencer J., 2015. The role of imaging in the diagnosis and management of renal stone disease in pregnancy. Clinical Radiology, 70(12), pp.1462-1471"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98310"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"453"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98310"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T12:37:55+09